6 minutes English.

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com.

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6 minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
I'm Neil.

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.000
And I'm Georgie.

6
00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
So Georgie, I'd like to know if you have any brothers or sisters and

7
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:20.000
if you get on well with them.

8
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:22.000
Yes, I do.

9
00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:24.000
I have a sister and we get on very well.

10
00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:27.000
We didn't use to, but now that we're adults, we get on well.

11
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.000
Well, in this program we'll be discussing one of the closest relationships there is.

12
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:35.000
The connection between sisters.

13
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:37.000
We'll hear from three Irish sisters,

14
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:39.000
reuniting on a radio show.

15
00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:44.000
And from a psychotherapist on some stereotypes about sisterhood.

16
00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Plus we'll be learning some useful new vocabulary too.

17
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
And remember if you want to read along while you listen,

18
00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:54.000
you can find the script for this program on our website.

19
00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.000
BBCLearningEnglish.com.

20
00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:57.000
Yeah, great idea.

21
00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Now, whether you have one or not,

22
00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:02.000
our history and culture is full of sisters.

23
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.000
From the fairy tale of Cinderella and her ugly sisters

24
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.000
to tennis players, Venus and Serena Williams.

25
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.000
And currently two sisters, Ellie and Rachel Reeves,

26
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:14.000
a senior ministers in the British government.

27
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:17.000
So Neil, my question for you is this.

28
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.000
What is Rachel Reeves' government job?

29
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:22.000
Is she A, home secretary?

30
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.000
B, foreign secretary?

31
00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:27.000
Or see, Chancellor of the Exchequer?

32
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Well, I think the answer is C,

33
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:32.000
the Chancellor of the Exchequer,

34
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:35.000
which is the name for the finance minister in the UK.

35
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:40.000
Okay, Neil, we'll find out if that's the correct answer later in the program.

36
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:45.000
Newlomer Govon, the presenter of BBC Radio 4's Woman's Hour,

37
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:46.000
has two sisters.

38
00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:49.000
The vote, Liv and Ireland, so they're joining me on a video call.

39
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:51.000
Hello, island. Hello, Vera.

40
00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:53.000
Welcome to Woman's Hour.

41
00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:55.000
Hello. Hello. Hi.

42
00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:58.000
Newlomer was born in Dublin and moved to New York,

43
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:00.000
then London to work as a journalist,

44
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:02.000
while her two sisters stayed in Ireland.

45
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Here she introduces her older sister, Vera and younger sister,

46
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:11.000
Ileen, for a BBC Radio 4 women's hour special about sisterhood.

47
00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:15.000
Newlomer was a little worried what her sisters would say about her on the radio.

48
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:17.000
So let's listen in and find out.

49
00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Ileen, what would you say if you were described by relationship as sisters?

50
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:27.000
Very connected, I think, and we do get on very well, which I'm proud to say.

51
00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:29.000
Yes, I'm sorry.

52
00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:31.000
I'm going to put you on the spot, Vera.

53
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.000
What word would you use to describe me as a sister?

54
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
I couldn't give you word, but you definitely marched to your own drum.

55
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:41.000
What would that word be?

56
00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:43.000
Independent, definitely.

57
00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.000
You liked to control the situation.

58
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
Ileen thinks she gets on with her sisters.

59
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:53.000
To get on with someone means to like them and have a good relationship with them.

60
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Newlomer puts her older sister on the spot,

61
00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:59.000
by asking Vera to describe her in one word.

62
00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:04.000
When you put someone on the spot, you make them answer a difficult question then and there.

63
00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:07.000
Sometimes making them embarrassed or uncomfortable.

64
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
But Newlomer didn't need to worry what her sisters would say.

65
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Vera simply said that Newlomer marches to her own drum.

66
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:19.000
She does things in her own way, which may be different from how other people do things.

67
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:24.000
It seems Vera and Nula and Ileen have remained close friends as they've grown up.

68
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:29.000
But the relationship between older, middle and younger sisters isn't always so harmonious.

69
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:34.000
Let's listen to BBC Radio 4's Women's Hour Special Program,

70
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.000
as Nula is joined by Psychotherapist Jennifer Glettill.

71
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:43.000
Thank you very much to Ileen and Vera, what a treat to have a chat with my sisters about

72
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:44.000
sisters.

73
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.000
I want to bring in Jennifer here who's listening to it all.

74
00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:51.000
Some of the stereotypes around siblings that the elder sister is bossy.

75
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:54.000
The middle sister is a peacemaker and the little sister is spoiled.

76
00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.000
That is not applying to our family.

77
00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.000
But I'm wondering is there any substance about it or why does that even get bandied around?

78
00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:03.000
We love giving people labels.

79
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:07.000
We like to put people into catargoes and then we can make sense of behaviours.

80
00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:14.000
That actually, since then, scientists find no proof of being these roles in the families.

81
00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:17.000
Nula discusses stereotypes about siblings.

82
00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.000
A word that means either brother or sister.

83
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
One stereotype is that the older sister is usually bossy.

84
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:26.000
She enjoys telling people what to do.

85
00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Another stereotype is that the younger sister is spoiled.

86
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:35.000
If you describe a child as spoiled, you mean they are allowed to do anything they want,

87
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:38.000
often with the result that they behave badly.

88
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:41.000
What do you think about these stereotypes, Georgie?

89
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:43.000
Are they true for you and your sister?

90
00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:48.000
I'm not sure I agree with these stereotypes because the older sister is meant to be bossy,

91
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.000
but my younger sister is the bossy one.

92
00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:52.000
I don't think I'm bossy at all.

93
00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:53.000
Well that's interesting.

94
00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:57.000
Jennifer did say that there's no scientific proof.

95
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:01.000
Anyway, it's time now to find out the answer to your question, Georgie.

96
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Yes, and my question was, what is Rachel Reeves' government job?

97
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:12.000
And you guessed she was the chancellor of the ex-checker, which was the correct answer.

98
00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:13.000
Well done, Neil.

99
00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Hooray!

100
00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned in this program.

101
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:23.000
Starting with the phrasal verb, get on with someone, meaning to have a good relationship with them.

102
00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:30.000
If you put someone on the spot, you cause them embarrassment by forcing them to answer a difficult question at that very moment.

103
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:36.000
If you march to your own drum, you do things in your own unique way, regardless of how other people do them.

104
00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:39.000
A sibling can mean either a brother or sister.

105
00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:43.000
People who are bossy and joy telling other people what to do.

106
00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:50.000
And finally, a spoiled child is allowed to do whatever they want, becoming badly behaved as a result.

107
00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:56.000
Once again, our six minutes are up, but remember to head over to BBCLearningEnglish.com,

108
00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:02.000
where you can find loads more fun and helpful resources, including a worksheet and quiz for this program.

109
00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:03.000
Bye for now.

110
